          "subtype": "message",
          "text": "Perfect! My analysis is confirmed. Let me create a summary of my findings:\n\n## Fault Localization Summary\n\nI have successfully identified the source of the bug in the Linux kernel iwlwifi driver:\n\n### **Bug Location**\n- **File**: `drivers/net/wireless/intel/iwlwifi/pcie/drv.c`\n- **Data Structure**: `iwl_dev_info_table[]` (static array starting at line 978)\n- **Function using it**: `iwl_pci_probe()` (lines 1031-1042)\n\n### **Root Cause**\nThe Intel Wireless-AC 9260 card (PCI device ID `0x2526`) is missing three specific subdevice ID entries in the device info table:\n- `0x4010`\n- `0x4018`\n- `0x401C`\n\nThese missing entries prevent the driver from selecting the correct firmware configuration (`iwl9260_2ac_160_cfg`) for these hardware variants. Without them, the probe function falls back to a generic catch-all configuration that uses `iwl9000_trans_cfg`, which is insufficient for proper firmware loading.\n\n### **Evidence**\n1. The `iwl_dev_info_table` at line 978 contains entries for many 0x2526 subdevice IDs (0x0010, 0x0014, 0x0018, 0x001C, 0x6010, 0x6014, 0x8010, 0x8014, 0xA014, 0xE010, 0xE014, 0x0030, 0x0038, 0x003C, 0x4030)\n2. The probe function (lines 1031-1042) searches this table for exact device/subdevice ID matches\n3. The missing subdevice IDs (0x4010, 0x4018, 0x401C) should follow the same pattern as existing entries and use the 9260 160MHz configuration\n\nThe fault localization results have been written to `/workspace/fault_localization_result.json`.",
